<div id="comment_status_64230134" class="commentstatus"></div>
<div id="comment_64230134" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_64230134" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a id="comment_link_64230134" name="comment_link_64230134" href="//news.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23221838&amp;cid=64230134" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64230134)" >Re:</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64230134" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64230134); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~burtosis">burtosis</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~burtosis">( 1124179 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64230134"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64230134"><p><div class="quote"><p>40% isn't a bad rule of thumb for power plant efficiency - some do up to 60% but that's about it.  In the end it's got be less than Carnot efficiency which is 1 - T_cold/T_hot.  Since T_cold is going to be in the vicinity of 250-280K (on Earth anyway) you need a crazy hot heat source to do a lot better.</p></div><p>And that&rsquo;s why Carnot efficiency is kinda dumb, it&rsquo;s absolute and lacks perspective.  You can use the earths heat as the hot source and the cold of space to make <a href="https://www.cnet.com/home/energy-and-utilities/solar-panels-that-work-at-night-developed-at-stanford/" title="cnet.com">dark solar panels<span class="substr"> </span></a> [cnet.com] for nearly unlimited energy but at a density at best 10% of solar due to the thermal barrier that exists as the infra red link to the cold side reservoir.  It&rsquo;s far more realistic to use relative efficiency which replaces absolute zero with ambient temperature, as it&rsquo;s a what you pay for efficiency and does</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64230134">

</div>
</div>

