			<h4><a id="comment_link_64229864" name="comment_link_64229864" href="//news.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23221838&amp;cid=64229864" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64229864)" >Re:</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64229864" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64229864); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~burtosis">burtosis</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~burtosis">( 1124179 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64229864"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64229864"><p><div class="quote"><p> They can't get 300% COP below -25C, more like 200% or even 100%.</p><span class="substr"> </span></div><p>Air exchange ones, no. Ground based ones not true at all, they are unaffected by air temperature and have far greater efficiency because buried to a significant depth they experience far warmer temperatures on average in colder climates.</p><p><div class="quote"><p> What I'm seeing in problems with heat pumps is that they can take a lot of power for any house that is above average in floor space.</p></div><p>Thats because there is a considerable amount of power required to heat a home, natural gas delivers incredible kW of power for a low pressure small diameter line.  Natural gas is, on average, roughly three times cheaper per unit of energy in most economies around the world.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64229864">

